# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We needed to delete "columns" that are not lexicographically sorted therefore we will need 2 loops and will have to travel across the matrix in column-wise fashion
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The vector given is 1-D but it is a vector of strings so it can be thought of as a 2-D array with row elements as the strings and column elements as the individual characters of the string 
Outer loop will iterate across the columns.
No. if columns = length of string 

Inner loop will iterate across the rows 
No. of rows = no. of elements in the vector 

if ASCII value of element of column i is greater than ASCII value of element of column i+1 then it is not sorted and we increase the count 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n^2) - 2 nested for loops so n square time complexity

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1) - declared only one additional variable to keep track of count so constant space complexity

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int minDeletionSize(vector<string>& strs) {
        // ELEMENTS SHOULD BE SORTED LEXICOGRAPHICALLY - IN ALPHABETICAL ORDER **COLUMN WISE** 

        int n = strs.size();
        int cnt = 0 ; 
        // have to check column-wise therefore outerloop for columns
        for (int i = 0 ; i<strs[0].size() ; i++)
        {
            // inner loop for rows 
            for (int j = 0 ; j<strs.size()-1; j++)
            {
                // if ASCII value of previous element is greater than that of next then it is not sorted, we increase count and break the loop to move on to the next column
                if(strs[j][i]>strs[j+1][i])
                {
                    cnt++;
                    break;
                }
                else continue ; 
            }
        }
        return cnt ; 
    }
};
```

